This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with techniques for gathering representative information about the World Wide Web. It may also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category as it discusses random walks on the web. Additionally, it involves analyzing data sets, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also proposes improvements based on experimental results, which could place it in the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing outcomes in detail, which could place it in the Systems and Control (cs.SD) sub-category.
